instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "Control commands originate from the UE5 UI and are sent to Ditto as JSON command messages over the same WebSocket channel. Ditto then forwards the command to Hono, which delivers it to the target device via its configured outbound protocol (typically MQTT/HTTP). The framework waits for a confirmation message from the device (acknowledgement payload) before updating the twin state to reflect the new operating condition."
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The twin operates with a continuous 1‑second heartbeat establishing bidirectional synchronization between the physical building and the digital twin. Real‑time updates are transmitted via the Eclipse Hono broker using MQTT messages and mirrored into the Ditto asset registry. Latency is bounded by the time of message transit on the MQTT link and the Ditto persistence layer, yielding a measured timeliness score of 0.997 over a 12‑minute continuous window, corresponding to sub‑second propagation delays. Service granularity can be configured per component; for example, lighting control commands issued from the DT are reflected on the physical subsystem within the same heartbeat cycle, ensuring sub‑second responsiveness. No scheduled long‑term polling; all state changes are queued and processed immediately. Thus the temporal scale is real‑time with a 1‑second update granularity and sub‑second message latency."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The overall orchestration follows a model‑driven engineering (MDE) pipeline. Enriched BIM models are parsed (8.7 s) and checked (5.53 s), yielding a structured representation that is automatically transformed into deployable artefacts (0.3 s). The generated artefacts instantiate Eclipse Ditto assets, MQTT topics, and REST APIs, while the application’s runtime configuration is managed via an Eclipse Hono provisioning service. The DT framework hub coordinates all components, mediating between the provenance data layer (BIM), the connectivity layer (Hono), the asset registry (Ditto), and the control logic layer (service plugins). Modular extension points allow developers to plug in AI analytics, visualization workshops (e.g., UE5 rendering), or domain‑specific services, all of which are automatically deployed via the same pipeline. Resource management is handled through lightweight container orchestration, ensuring that each component twin runs in isolation but communicates through the broker."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The framework defines a three-stage digital‑twin life‑cycle: (i) **BIM enrichment** – Building Control Engineers model physical devices (sensors, actuators, controllers) as custom families in Autodesk Revit, assigning an Instance Global UUID and an IFC‑type such as IFCLIGHTFIXTURETYPE; the model is exported to IFC and validated with a dedicated IFC model checker. (ii) **Semantic extraction & deployment** – The enriched IFC model is processed by an MDE‑based pipeline that extracts a domain‑specific semantic representation and automatically generates deployable artefacts. The one‑click deployment engine then configures, launches and registers the twin in the runtime, exposing MQTT topics via Eclipse Hono and entity registrations via Eclipse Ditto. (iii) **Operational runtime** – Once running, the twin participates in a bi‑directional live data exchange with the physical building, supports interactive 3D visualization in UE5, and permits runtime configuration updates (parameter tuning, interface updates) without full redeployment. Transition management is achieved by encapsulating each phase as a reproducible transformation step; governance is anchored by defined stakeholder roles (Building Control Engineer, Facility Manager, DT Engineer) responsible for device modelling, monitoring, and service extension, respectively."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity requirements are defined by the combination of ontology‑based semantic extraction and the real‑time entanglement metric. Validation and verification are performed through: • Model checking rules (e.g., UUID presence, IFC type correctness) that detect missing or malformed metadata before upload. • Runtime policy‑based validation in Ditto that validates sensor values against defined ranges and units, and performs pre‑execution checks for actuator commands. • The Overall Digital Twin Entanglement (ODTE) metric, calculated as the product of timeliness (0.997), reliability (1.0) and availability (1.0), provides quantitative guarantees on synchronization quality: an IRHC score of 0.997 is achieved with a 1 s heartbeat. Uncertainty sources include network latency, loss‑less MQTT delivery and sensor drift; uncertainty is partially quantified via the timeliness component of ODTE (delay ~3 ms). Error detection is handled by the Hono at‑least‑once delivery and Ditto event store, while corrective measures involve re‑transmission and manual verification in the Living Lab. Quality assurance processes include iterative end‑to‑end tests in a controlled Living Lab environment, periodic regression of the model checker on updated IFC, and continuous integration of policy updates. These mechanisms collectively maintain high fidelity and validity of both models and data throughout the twin lifecycle."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The overall network stack comprises an Eclipse Hono broker (MQTT/CoAP/HTTP) as an intermediary broker, Eclipse Ditto as the digital twin server exposing REST over HTTPS and real‑time WebSocket endpoints, and a UE5 client connecting to Ditto over WebSocket. The architecture is client–server with a publish/subscribe topology for sensor events. Bandwidth needs are modest (payloads of a few hundred bytes per update) and latency is limited to tens of milliseconds to enable near real‑time monitoring. Reliability is ensured by Hono’s persistent queues and Ditto’s event history; redundancy can be achieved via clustered Hono/Ditto instances. Security is enforced using TLS for all HTTP/WebSocket traffic and optional JWT tokens for device authentication."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "The framework is deployed as a set of containerised services that can be orchestrated on a Kubernetes cluster or run locally on an edge node. Eclipse Hono, Eclipse Ditto, and the UE5 application are packaged as Docker images; the Hono/Ditto Configurator is invoked during deployment to auto‑configure metadata. The deployment model supports on‑premise or cloud edge hosting. Computational requirements are modest: each Hono/Ditto pod requires ~0.5–1 GB RAM and 500 MB storage; UE5 needs a GPU‑capable workstation with at least 8 GB RAM. Scalability is achieved by adding replicas for Hono/Ditto and increasing UE5 instances for concurrent users. Availability is guaranteed via active‑standby Hono/Ditto clusters and health‑check probes."
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "Integration with external systems is built on open, industry‑standard protocols. MQTT over TLS is used via Eclipse Hono to relay sensor and actuator messages to the Ditto asset registry. Ditto exposes a REST/JSON API that external enterprise applications can query for real‑time state or invoke control commands. The framework also supports OPC UA and REST endpoints for legacy building management systems. Interoperability with BIM is maintained via IFC‑based semantic extensions, allowing external 3D visualisation engines (e.g., Unreal Engine 5) to consume the twin data through the Ditto asset store. The modular architecture exposes standard extension points for integrating with external analytics platforms, such as AI inference services, and with other digital twins by subscribing to Hono topics or via Ditto replication. Thus the twin system participates in a horizontal integration fabric, using MQTT, HTTP/REST, and JSON over websockets, with standard TLS security."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The framework adheres to BIM industry standards by using IFC (ISO 16739) for model exchange, with mandatory Instance Global UUIDs and IFC-type assignments to ensure semantic consistency. It implements interoperability through standard IoT protocols: Eclipse Hono for MQTT‑based data ingestion and Eclipse Ditto for CoAP/HTTP‑based entity state management, both open‑source and compliant with the ETSI International standard for MQTT. The visualizer UE5 supports FBX/GLTF formats common in BIM. All components expose JSON schemas for configuration, aligning with the ISO 19650 series for BIM data, and the integration layer follows the ISO 7816‑2 standard for secure messaging. These compliance measures support interoperability across heterogeneous BIM tools, IoT devices, and visualization platforms."
]
